ow understood as a broad movement whose impact was felt just as strongly in the prose genres: the short story, the novel, the essay, and the journalistic crónica [chronicle]. Conceived as an introduction to modernismo as well as an account of the current state of the art of modernismo studies, this book examines the movement's contribution to the various Spanish American literary genres, its main authors [from Martí and Nájera to Darío and Rodó], its social and historical context, and its continuing relevance to the work of contemporary Spanish American authors such as Gabriel García Márquez, Sergio Ramírez, aargas Llosa. ANÍBAL GONZÁLEZ-PÉREZ is Professor of Modern Latin American Literature at Yale University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aModernism (Literature)zLatin America. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticismy20th century. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aFrench Symbolist aesthetics.  aGabriel García Márquez.  aMario Vargas Llosa.  aModernismo.  aNew World.  aSergio Ramírez.  aSpain.  aSpanish America.  aSpanish-language literary movement.  acultural cosmopolitanism.  aliterary technique.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846155246?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155246/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles